SIMPLE: fallow
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fallow
<hw>Fal"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>fealu</ets>,
<ets>fealo</ets>, pale yellow or red; akin to D. <ets>vaal</ets> fallow,
faded, OHG. <ets>falo</ets>, G. <ets>falb</ets>, <ets>fahl</ets>, Icel.
<ets>f⟦oum⟧lr</ets>, and prob. to Lith. <ets>palvas</ets>, OSlav.
<ets>plav⟦ucr⟧</ets> white, L. <ets>pallidus</ets> pale,
<ets>pallere</ets> to be pale, Gr. <grk>polio`s</grk> gray, Skr.
<ets>palita</ets>. Cf. <er>Pale</er>, <er>Favel</er>, <pos>a.</pos>,
<er>Favor</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pale red or pale yellow; <as>as,
a <ex>fallow</ex> deer or greyhound</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Cf. <er>Fallow</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>Left
untilled or unsowed after plowing; uncultivated; <as>as, <ex>fallow</ex>
ground</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Fallow chat</b></col>, <col><b>Fallow
finch</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small European bird,
the wheatear (<spn>Saxicola ⟦oe⟧nanthe</spn>). See
<er>Wheatear</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fallow
<hw>Fal"low</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[So called from the
<ets>fallow</ets>, or somewhat yellow, color of naked ground; or perh.
akin to E. <ets>felly</ets>, <pos>n.</pos>, cf. MHG. <ets>valgen</ets>
to plow up, OHG. <ets>felga</ets> felly, harrow.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Plowed land.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who . . . pricketh his blind horse over the
<qex>fallows</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Land that has lain a year or more untilled or
unseeded; land plowed without being sowed for the season.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The plowing of <qex>fallows</qex> is a benefit to land.</q>
<rj><qau>Mortimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The plowing or tilling of land, without sowing it
for a season; <as>as, summer <ex>fallow</ex>, properly conducted, has
ever been found a sure method of destroying weeds</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be a complete summer <qex>fallow</qex>, land is rendered tender
and mellow. The <qex>fallow</qex> gives it a better tilth than can be
given by a fallow crop.</q> <rj><qau>Sinclair.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fallow crop</b></col>, <cd>the crop taken from a green
fallow.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Green fallow</b></col>,
<cd>fallow whereby land is rendered mellow and clean from weeds, by
cultivating some green crop, as turnips, potatoes, etc.</cd>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fallow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fallow
<hw>Fal"low</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fallowed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Fallowing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Fallow</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <def>To plow, harrow, and break up, as land,
without seeding, for the purpose of destroying weeds and insects, and
rendering it mellow; <as>as, it is profitable to <ex>fallow</ex> cold,
strong, clayey land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fallow deer</ent>⟦br⟧
